description:
secretx-keyring/src/lib.rs:184-200 — both inventory submits use fully-qualified paths inside their factory closures:

```rust
inventory::submit!(secretx_core::BackendRegistration {
    name: "keyring",
    factory: |uri: &str| {
        KeyringBackend::from_uri(uri)
            .map(|b| std::sync::Arc::new(b) as std::sync::Arc<dyn secretx_core::SecretStore>)
    },
});
```

Imports already cover `SecretStore` and `WritableSecretStore` at the top of the file (line 38). The remaining items `std::sync::Arc` could be brought in with `use std::sync::Arc;` at the top, and `BackendRegistration` / `WritableBackendRegistration` could similarly be imported. The current full-path usage is a half-step: the trait imports already exist but the closures still use full paths.

Idiomatic Rust prefers consistent imports. Either fully-qualify everywhere or import everywhere; the mix is a minor readability cost. The sibling crate secretx-wolfhsm uses imports at the top.

Resolution: `use std::sync::Arc; use secretx_core::{BackendRegistration, WritableBackendRegistration};` at top, simplify the closure bodies. Diff is small.
